
# 🚆✊🏿 The Pullman Porters

📂 **Type:** Historical Group  
📅 **Date Created:** 2025-02-03  
📅 **Last Updated:** 2025-02-03

---

## 🏛️ Overview

The **Pullman Porters** were **African American men** who worked as **porters** for the **Pullman Company’s luxury sleeping cars** from the late 19th century to the mid-20th century. As one of the **largest employers of Black men** during the Jim Crow era, Pullman Porters were both symbols of economic opportunity and a reflection of the **racial inequalities** of the time. Their struggle for **fair wages, dignity, and labor rights** led to the formation of the **Brotherhood of Sleeping Car Porters (BSCP)**, which became a major force in **Black labor activism and the Civil Rights Movement**.

---

## 📌 Key Details

- **🚂 Employer:** The Pullman Company
- **📅 Active Years:** 1867 – 1969
- **👤 Key Figures:**
    - **[[A. Philip Randolph]]** – President of the **Brotherhood of Sleeping Car Porters (BSCP)**
    - **[[Ashley Totten]]** – Co-founder & union organizer
    - **Edna Thomas** – Leader of the BSCP **Ladies Auxiliary**
- **🏆 Major Achievements:**
    - **First Black labor union recognized by the AFL (1937)**
    - **Higher wages and better working conditions**
    - **Influenced the Civil Rights Movement**

---

## 📜 Timeline

- **🗓️ 1867:** George Pullman hires formerly enslaved Black men as **Pullman Porters**.
- **🗓️ 1925:** **Brotherhood of Sleeping Car Porters (BSCP)** founded by **A. Philip Randolph**.
- **🗓️ 1937:** BSCP **wins union recognition** and secures **wage increases & better working conditions**.
- **🗓️ 1941:** BSCP organizes the **March on Washington Movement**, leading to **Executive Order 8802**, banning racial discrimination in defense industries.
- **🗓️ 1963:** BSCP leadership helps organize the **March on Washington for Jobs and Freedom**.
- **🗓️ 1969:** Pullman Company **ends sleeper car service**, leading to the decline of Pullman Porters.

